<ns2:para xmlns:ns2="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.jboss.architecture.introParagraph">

  The architecture of JBoss is dominantly driven by the <ns3:emphasis xmlns:ns3="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">modifiability</ns3:emphasis>,
  <ns4:emphasis xmlns:ns4="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">portability</ns4:emphasis> and <ns5:emphasis xmlns:ns5="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">usability</ns5:emphasis>
  quality attributes. It is an extremely modular design which, in its core, provides
  <ns6:itemizedlist xmlns:ns6="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    <ns7:listitem xmlns:ns7="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns8:para xmlns:ns8="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
       <ns9:emphasis xmlns:ns9="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">JBossServer</ns9:emphasis>, the EJB container,       
    </ns8:para></ns7:listitem>
    <ns10:listitem xmlns:ns10="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns11:para xmlns:ns11="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      and a <ns12:emphasis xmlns:ns12="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Java Management Extension (JMX) infrastructure</ns12:emphasis>.
    </ns11:para></ns10:listitem>
  </ns6:itemizedlist>
</ns2:para>